Sharing news from the California State Department of Education for extra funding available for families experiencing food insecurity. If you are not currently receiving services, you will need to apply for this program. Please read the article for details.
This does not affect your ability to participate in YCUSD to go meal service.
shared_text:
California Department of Education
April 30 at 11:12 AM ¬∑

State Superintendent Tony Thurmond announced that the U.S. Department of Agriculture has approved a new food assistance program for children throughout the state who are living in households struggling with food insecurity. The Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) program provides electronic food benefits to families equal to the value of meals children eligible for free or reduced-priced meals would have received at school.

Read more: https://www.cde.ca.gov/nr/ne/yr20/yr20rel29.asp

post_text: On April 1, 2020, Governor Gavin Newsom and State Superintendent of Schools Tony Thurmond recommended that schools prepare to provide distance learning to students through the end of the school year. In addition, the Bi-County Health Official announced the COVID-19 virus is likely to peak in our area in mid to late May. As always, student and staff safety is our highest priority. Therefore, we are making the decision to close all YCUSD school campuses for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. All teaching and learning will occur through distance learning. For the full message, please visit our website: http://www.ycusd.org/announcements/?capostid=20937

Parents and students of Yuba City Unified School District,

Currently, the school district plans to re-open schools for instruction after spring break. However, it is unknown at this time if that will be possible. In an effort to be prepared with alternative instructional options, we need your input. We want families to have their preferred delivery of instruction for each of their students. You can choose from online or print options. If computers are needed, we can help with that too. Please complete this short survey so we can provide what is needed for each student. Please submit one survey for each student.

Survey Link: https://forms.gle/6LfBqYVNh4ARTEDX7

Today, the Sutter/Yuba County Public Health Official in coordination with the California Department of Public Health and the Governor‚Äôs Office, issued guidance to postpone or cancel all mass gatherings of more than 250 people. Examples of non-essential events that will be canceled at least through March:

‚Ä¢ Sporting events
‚Ä¢ Assemblies
‚Ä¢ Concerts/drama performances
‚Ä¢ Parent nights
‚Ä¢ Field trips
‚Ä¢ Facility rentals by outside groups

There are no recommendations to close schools as there are no known cases of COVID-19 in Yuba and Sutter counties at this time. ALL routine school attendance activities will continue such as:

‚Ä¢ Regularly scheduled classes, support services, and the after school extended learning program
‚Ä¢ School interventions and tutoring
‚Ä¢ Staff meetings

The District will continue to work with local health officials to determine appropriate measures for future events. The safety of our students, staff, and community is our top priority.
